---
import { getProject } from '../../data/projects';
import ProjectLayout from '../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro';

const project = getProject('ship-model');

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'missouri', label: '01. USS Missouri' },
  { id: 'atlanta', label: '02. USS Atlanta' },
  { id: 'competitions', label: '03. Competitions' },
  { id: 'highlights', label: '04. Highlights' }
];
---

<ProjectLayout
  title={project.title}
  description={project.description}
  dateRange={project.dateRange}
  tags={project.tags}
  heroMedia={project.cover}
  toc={tocItems}
>
  <section id="missouri" class="scroll-mt-28 space-y-5">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white">01. USS Missouri BB-63</h2>
    <div class="rounded-lg overflow-hidden border border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-800 bg-slate-100 dark:bg-slate-950">
      <img src="/assets/ship-model/Missouri.jpg" alt="USS Missouri BB-63 scale model" class="w-full h-auto object-cover" />
    </div>
    <p class="leading-relaxed text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-300 font-light">
      Built from Tamiya's 1/700 Missouri kit, this model includes aftermarket metal photo-etched parts, gun barrels, and a wooden deck.
    </p>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white">Build Process</h3>
    <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-300 list-none p-0 m-0 font-normal">
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="font-mono text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-500 text-xs mt-0.5">-</span> Hull and deck bonded with plastic cement, then masked and brush painted with Measure 22 camouflage.</li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="font-mono text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-500 text-xs mt-0.5">-</span> Superstructure assembled, detailed with photo-etched parts, and acrylic brush painted in haze gray.</li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="font-mono text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-500 text-xs mt-0.5">-</span> Wooden deck painted blue and attached, with fine details such as cannons, anti-aircraft weaponry, stairs, and railings added afterward.</li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="font-mono text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-500 text-xs mt-0.5">-</span> Weathering applied with oil paint and acrylic wash, followed by rigging, flags, and a glossy wet-deck effect.</li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="font-mono text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-500 text-xs mt-0.5">-</span> Ocean base shaped from foam, air-dry clay, epoxy, paint, and cotton wave crests.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="leading-relaxed text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-300 font-light">
      The full build process took around seven months, working a few hours a day for a few days per week.
    </p>
    <div class="rounded-lg overflow-hidden border border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-800 bg-slate-100 dark:bg-slate-950">
      <img src="/assets/ship-model/Missouri_His.jpg" alt="Historical USS Missouri reference" class="w-full h-auto object-cover" />
    </div>
    <p class="leading-relaxed text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-300 font-light">
      USS Missouri BB-63 was an Iowa-class battleship commissioned in 1944. She served in World War II, the Korean War, and Operation Desert Storm, and is best known as the site of Japan's formal surrender on September 2, 1945.
    </p>
  </section>

  <hr class="border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-800" />

  <section id="atlanta" class="scroll-mt-28 space-y-5">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white">02. USS Atlanta CL-51</h2>
    <div class="rounded-lg overflow-hidden border border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-800 bg-slate-100 dark:bg-slate-950">
      <img src="/assets/ship-model/Atlanta.jpg" alt="USS Atlanta CL-51 scale model" class="w-full h-auto object-cover" />
    </div>
    <p class="leading-relaxed text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-300 font-light">
      Built from the Very Fire 1/350 USS Atlanta Deluxe kit, this model includes plastic hull parts, sprues, photo-etched parts, and brass gun barrels.
    </p>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white">Build Process</h3>
    <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-300 list-none p-0 m-0 font-normal">
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="font-mono text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-500 text-xs mt-0.5">-</span> Hull, bridge, funnels, and superstructure sections bonded with plastic cement.</li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="font-mono text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-500 text-xs mt-0.5">-</span> Photo-etched details such as porthole rims and railings attached with CA glue.</li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="font-mono text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-500 text-xs mt-0.5">-</span> Late 1942 camouflage brush painted by hand, including hull, deck, and superstructure patterns.</li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="font-mono text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-500 text-xs mt-0.5">-</span> Fine parts, masts, weathering, rigging, clear coats, and flags added for final detail.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="leading-relaxed text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-300 font-light">
      The build took about six months, working a few days per week for a couple of hours at a time.
    </p>
    <div class="rounded-lg overflow-hidden border border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-800 bg-slate-100 dark:bg-slate-950">
      <img src="/assets/ship-model/Atlanta_his.jpg" alt="Historical USS Atlanta reference" class="w-full h-auto object-cover" />
    </div>
    <p class="leading-relaxed text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-300 font-light">
      USS Atlanta CL-51 was the lead ship of the Atlanta-class light cruisers. Designed as an anti-aircraft cruiser, she served in the Pacific and played a major role in the Battle of Guadalcanal before being scuttled after heavy damage on November 13, 1942.
    </p>
  </section>

  <hr class="border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-800" />

  <section id="competitions" class="scroll-mt-28 space-y-5">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white">03. Model Ship Building Competitions</h2>
    <p class="leading-relaxed text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-300 font-light">
      I participated in Wisconsin Maritime Museum model ship building competitions, showcasing craftsmanship and historical accuracy.
    </p>
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-5">
      <div class="rounded-lg overflow-hidden border border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-800 bg-slate-100 dark:bg-slate-950">
        <img src="/assets/ship-model/ShipModelAward.jpeg" alt="Model ship competition award" class="w-full h-full object-cover" />
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-lg overflow-hidden border border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-800 bg-slate-100 dark:bg-slate-950">
        <img src="/assets/ship-model/ShipModelMedal.jpeg" alt="Model ship competition medal" class="w-full h-full object-cover" />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr class="border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-800" />

  <section id="highlights" class="scroll-mt-28 space-y-4">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white">04. Highlights</h2>
    <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-300 list-none p-0 m-0 font-normal">
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="font-mono text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-500 text-xs mt-0.5">-</span> Scale model construction with plastic cement bonding and photo-etch assembly.</li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="font-mono text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-500 text-xs mt-0.5">-</span> Authentic historical camouflage schemes and military paint patterns.</li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="font-mono text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-500 text-xs mt-0.5">-</span> Weathering and finishing with oils, acrylics, washes, and protective coatings.</li>
      <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="font-mono text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-500 text-xs mt-0.5">-</span> Detailed ocean bases using foam, clay, epoxy, paint, and cotton wave effects.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</ProjectLayout>
